b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p3_lattice_energy" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n    \n    \n    \n    <head>\n        <title>Lattice Energy</title>\n        <objref idref="ionic_bond"/>\n    </head>\n    \n    <body>\n        \n        <p>An ionic compound is stable because of the electrostatic attraction between its positive\n            and negative ions. The lattice energy of a compound is a measure of the strength of this\n            attraction. The <extra><anchor>lattice energy (\xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em><sub>lattice</sub>)</anchor><meaning><material><p>energy required to separate one mole of an ionic solid into its component gaseous ions</p></material></meaning></extra> of an\n            ionic compound is defined as the energy required to separate one mole of the solid into\n            its component gaseous ions. For the ionic solid MX, the lattice energy is the enthalpy\n            change of the process:</p>\n        <formula>$$MX(s)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;M^{n+}(\\mathrm g)\\;+\\;X^{n-}(\\mathrm\n            g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta H_\\mathrm{lattice}$$</formula>\n        <p>Note that we are using the convention where the ionic solid is separated into ions, so\n            our lattice energies will be endothermic (positive values). Some texts use the\n            equivalent but opposite convention, defining lattice energy as the energy released when\n            separate ions combine to form a lattice and giving negative (exothermic) values. Thus,\n            if you are looking up lattice energies in another reference, be certain to check which\n            definition is being used. In both cases, a larger magnitude for lattice energy indicates\n            a more stable ionic compound. For sodium chloride, \xce\x94<em style="italic"\n                >H</em><sub>lattice</sub> = 769 kJ. Thus, it requires 769 kJ to separate one mole of\n            solid NaCl into gaseous Na<sup>+</sup> and Cl<sup>\xe2\x80\x93</sup> ions. When one mole each of\n            gaseous Na<sup>+</sup> and Cl<sup>\xe2\x80\x93</sup> ions form solid NaCl, 769 kJ of heat is released.</p>\n        \n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n        <dl>\n            <dt>Lattice Energy</dt>\n            <dd>\n                <p>The lattice energy \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em><sub>lattice</sub> of an ionic crystal can\n                    be expressed by the following equation (derived from Coulomb\xe2\x80\x99s law, governing the forces\n                    between electric charges): </p>\n                <formula>$$\\mathrm\\Delta H_\\mathrm{lattice}\\;=\\frac{\\;C(Z^+)(Z^-)}{R_o}$$</formula>\n                <p>in which <em style="italic">C</em> is a constant that depends on the type of crystal\n                    structure; <em style="italic">Z</em><sup>+</sup> and <em style="italic">Z</em><sup>\xe2\x80\x93</sup> are the charges on the ions; and \n                    <em style="italic">R<sub>o</sub></em> is the\n                    interionic distance (the sum of the radii of the positive and negative ions). </p>\n            </dd>\n        </dl>\n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n        <p>  \n            The lattice energy of an ionic crystal increases rapidly as the charges of the ions increase\n            and the sizes of the ions decrease. When all other parameters are kept constant,\n            doubling the charge of both the cation and anion quadruples the lattice energy. For\n            example, the lattice energy of LiF (<em style="italic">Z</em><sup>+</sup> and <em style="italic">Z</em><sup>\xe2\x80\x93</sup> = 1) is 1023 kJ/mol,\n            whereas that of MgO (<em style="italic">Z</em><sup>+</sup> and <em style="italic">Z</em><sup>\xe2\x80\x93</sup> = 2) is 3900 kJ/mol (<em\n                style="italic">R</em><sub>o</sub> is nearly the same\xe2\x80\x94about 200 pm for both\n            compounds).</p>\n        <p>Different interatomic distances produce different lattice energies. For example, we can\n            compare the lattice energy of MgF<sub>2</sub> (2957 kJ/mol) to that of MgI<sub>2</sub>\n            (2327 kJ/mol) to observe the effect on lattice energy of the smaller ionic size of\n            F<sup>\xe2\x80\x93</sup> as compared to I<sup>\xe2\x80\x93</sup>. The difference between lattice energies\n            of compounds is significantly more dependent on the charges of the ions rather than the\n            size of the ions because the variations between the sizes of the ions is relatively\n            small.</p>\n        <example>\n            <p>Which has the larger lattice energy, Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> or\n                Al<sub>2</sub>Se<sub>3</sub>?</p>\n            <p>In these two ionic compounds, the charges <em style="italic">Z</em><sup>+</sup> and <em style="italic">Z</em><sup>\xe2\x80\x93</sup> are the\n                same, so the difference in lattice energy will depend upon <em style="italic">R</em><sub>o</sub>. The\n                O<sup>2\xe2\x80\x93</sup> ion is smaller than the Se<sup>2\xe2\x80\x93</sup> ion. Thus,\n                Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> would have a shorter interionic distance than\n                Al<sub>2</sub>Se<sub>3</sub>, and Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> would have the\n                larger lattice energy.</p>\n        </example>\n        <wb:inline idref="lattice_energy_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n        <wb:inline idref="lattice_dnd_question" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n        \n        <wb:inline idref="lattice_energy_digt" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n        <wb:inline idref="lattice2_dnd_question" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n        \n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n            >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n            href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n            >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n        \n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'